author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Myanmar marks 10 years since the signing of the National Ceasefire Agreement (NCA), originally intended to end decades of conflict with ethnic armed groups. However, nearly five years after the military seized power in a coup, the prospects for peace appear increasingly remote. Many of the signatories have declared the agreement void, as the country endures a devastating civil war.

Al Jazeera spoke to Ko Htein, a former graphic designer who joined the armed resistance after witnessing violent crackdowns on peaceful anti-coup protests. Now a People’s Defence Force soldier, Ko Htein shares his hopes for unity among ethnic armed groups and a future federal Myanmar. Meanwhile, displaced civilians from Karen State continue to seek refuge by the border as junta forces push their offensive.

description:
Simone Gbagbo, Ivory Coast’s former First Lady once accused of war crimes, is running in October’s presidential election alongside ally Charles Ble Goude, who is barred from contesting. 
Both were acquitted by the International Criminal Court for their roles in the 2011 post-election violence that left thousands dead. 
Gbagbo’s supporters say the nation now needs “a mother” to unite a divided country. 
Opposition figures loyal to Laurent Gbagbo and Tidjane Thiam have been detained, and protests banned. 
Analysts warn the country risks sliding into another post-election crisis. 
Meanwhile, 83-year-old President Alassane Ouattara seeks a fourth term after changing the constitution. 
Many Ivorians fear the past may again shape their future.

Al Jazeera’s Nicolas Haque reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Thousands of Palestinian prisoners — most of them detained without charge — have been released from Israeli jails as part of the Gaza ceasefire deal. 
Reunions saw a mix of joy and sadness after people heard about the conditions their loved ones endured.
Electroshock devices, physical and sexual abuse, starvation and outbreaks of diseases. 
But several high-profile prisoners - including Marwan Barghouti - remain in Israeli jails. 
Hundreds more were forced into exile by Israel. 
And the majority return to rubble in Gaza and risk being arrested again in the Occupied West Bank. 
So, is it possible for former Palestinian prisoners to truly embrace freedom with life under occupation and the scars of Israeli detention? 

Presenter: Sami Zeidan

Guests:

Milena Ansari -  The Israel and Palestine Researcher at Human Rights Watch and trained in International Law. 

Basil Farraj - Assistant Professor at Birzeit University focusing on political prisoners and carceral violence. 

Fadia Barghouti
title: What's next for released Palestinian prisoners? | Inside Story

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Greek farmers are grappling with withheld EU subsidies amid a scandal that has implicated political figures and exposed fraudulent claims amounting to millions of dollars. 
While farmers struggle with rising costs for essentials such as feed and measures to combat livestock diseases, the government investigates allegations that funds were paid to individuals falsely claiming to be breeders. 
At least $25m has been confirmed as fraudulently obtained, with hundreds of millions potentially unaccounted for.
In northern Greece’s Serres region alone, 2,700 farmers are affected, many of whom rear indigenous species like water buffalo and rely heavily on subsidies. 
The fallout from the scandal compounds existing challenges for farmers, including climate change and high expenses, driving younger generations to seek opportunities abroad. 
Farmers accuse the government of complicity in the mismanagement of funds, further eroding trust in the system.

Al Jazeera’s John Psaropoulos reports from S
title: Greek farmers accuse government of complicity in EU subsidy scandal

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
At least 16 people have been killed and many more are feared trapped following a devastating fire at a garment factory in Dhaka, Bangladesh. 
The blaze, which took firefighters over three hours to control, also spread to a nearby chemical warehouse, triggering explosions and releasing toxic gas that contributed to the fatalities. 
Witnesses report that locked entrances and rooftop doors trapped workers inside, making escape impossible.
The factory, a subcontractor for international apparel brands, lacked proper fire safety approvals. 
For many families, the agonising wait for news of missing loved ones continues, with victims' remains reportedly so badly burned that DNA testing may be required for identification. 
Bangladesh’s garment sector, employing over four million people and accounting for more than 10% of the nation’s GDP, remains plagued by poor fire safety standards, highlighting the human cost of fast fashion.

Al Jazeera's Zein Basravi reports.

title: Bangladesh mourns victims of Dhaka factory inferno amid safety failures
